    "created_at": "2021-12-16T16:48:51Z",
    "updated_at": "2021-12-16T16:48:51Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "I'm generally in favor of defaulting to no git interaction, at least when inside an existing repo. I'm using forge inside a larger git repo, and at the moment I've resorted to deleting `.git` and `.gitmodules` after doing `forge init`, but then I have to `touch .git` just to get `forge test` to work when I want to run it.\r\n\r\nI'm also subverting the use of submodules for the contents of `lib` and just directly committed the contents of `lib` to the larger containing git repo, but that's not a principled stance, just me lazily dealing with the fact that `forge install` didn't play nice with my containing repo when creating submodules, and I don't really care if the upstream changes in this case. Also, I'd just as soon not deal with git submodules unless I need them.",
